 In his new role as a UN Habitat ambassador, the former Spurs man, through his organisation – Victor Wanyama Foundation, will seek to improve the lives of slum dwellers through initiatives that boost access to water, providing education and sanitation. 

“There is a lot that we can achieve, and for now it is just to do things step by step and make sure we make changes. We have done some other things before like giving scholarships to kids, so there is a lot we are going to do to change the lives of people  living in slum,” said Wanyama. 

Oumar Sylla, the Africa Director UN Habitat said that by partnering with Wanyama, they hope to reach more people. “There is more expected from us at the community level and that is the reason why we are here today to seal this memorandum of understanding.” 

Last year, through Victor Wanyama Foundation, the Kenya midfielder built a new house for a family of five who were living in an old structure at the Korogocho slums in Nairobi. Together with UN Habitat, he also provided 7,000 masks to Mathare and Kibera residents in August.   

Wanyama added that he is happy with the on going construction of his football academy in Busia. He said it will house world class facilities when complete. 



